<p id="p0040">We define the factor 
 <italic>r</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>i</italic>
 </sub>(
 <italic>t</italic>) as:
 <disp-formula id="fd10">
  <label>(10)</label>
  <math id="M15" altimg="si15.gif">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>r</mi>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mi>t</mi>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mo>
    <msup>
     <mi>e</mi>
     <mrow>
      <mo>−</mo>
      <mi>β</mi>
      <msub>
       <mi>C</mi>
       <mi>i</mi>
      </msub>
      <mrow>
       <mo>(</mo>
       <mi>t</mi>
       <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
    </msup>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mrow>
      <mn>1</mn>
      <mo linebreak="badbreak">+</mo>
      <mi>β</mi>
      <msub>
       <mi>C</mi>
       <mi>i</mi>
      </msub>
      <mrow>
       <mo>(</mo>
       <mi>t</mi>
       <mo>)</mo>
      </mrow>
     </mrow>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo>,</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <italic>β</italic> stands for a second dimensionless constant. In the global picture, the log likelihood function converges to the global log likelihood of the total correlation-dependent density 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M16" altimg="si16.gif">
   <mtext>Ξ</mtext>
  </math>
 </inline-formula>:
 <disp-formula id="fd11">
  <label>(11)</label>
  <math id="M17" altimg="si17.gif">
   <mrow>
    <munder>
     <mtext>lim</mtext>
     <mrow>
      <mi>t</mi>
      <mo linebreak="badbreak">→</mo>
      <mi>∞</mi>
     </mrow>
    </munder>
    <msub>
     <mi>l</mi>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </msub>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <mi>t</mi>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mo>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">−</mo>
    <mtext>log</mtext>
    <mrow>
     <mo>(</mo>
     <msub>
      <mtext>Ξ</mtext>
      <mi>i</mi>
     </msub>
     <mo>)</mo>
    </mrow>
    <mo>,</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <inline-formula>
  <math id="M18" altimg="si18.gif">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mtext>Ξ</mtext>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </msub>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </inline-formula> is approximated as the probability function 
 <italic>P</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>i</italic>
 </sub> of the path-dependent correlation:
 <disp-formula id="fd12">
  <label>(12)</label>
  <math id="M19" altimg="si19.gif">
   <mrow>
    <msub>
     <mi>P</mi>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo linebreak="goodbreak">≈</mo>
    <msub>
     <mtext>Ξ</mtext>
     <mi>i</mi>
    </msub>
    <mo>.</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>
</p>
